                    <a name="intro"></a>
                    <div class="helpTopLink">
                        <a href="blogging-help#top">Go to top</a>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Introduction</h3>
                    <p>
                        Blogging package provides simple extension for Plone to make blogging easier
                        with as little as possible modifications or extra content. But still use as much
                        as possible from Plone's default UI to let user's get familiar with extra
                        blogging features in a while.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        So, let's say that in most cases when you want to start simple personal blog,
                        default Plone installation without any extra add-ons provides almost all
                        you need.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For example you can create Folder / Large Plone Folder for blog posts, Smart
                        Folder as site frontpage with criteria to search contents of the blog folder
                        and then you can start blogging by creating News Items in the blog folder.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Yes that's fine but after while you end up with thinking about better
                        blog view template because folder summary view doesn't provide some extra
                        info about listed News Items like number of comments, permalink etc.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        And that's why the Blogging package was created and hopefully will save your
                        time in case you don't need complex blogging tool but still want a blog.
                    </p>
                    <br/>
                    
                    <a name="basic-usage"></a>
                    <div class="helpTopLink">
                        <a href="blogging-help#top">Go to top</a>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Basic usage</h3>
                    <p>
                        At first the blog folder has to be created. Go to wherever you want in your
                        plone site structure and add new folder or Large Plone Folder if you expect
                        a lot of posts.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The only trick how to turn new folder into blog folder is to tick the box
                        with label <b>Blog enabled</b> in the <b>Blog</b> section of the folder's edit form.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 1.</legend>
                            <img title="Create blog"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/create_blog.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <p><i><b>Note:</b> You can turn folders into blog anytime you want.</i></p>
                    
                    <p>
                        Additionally you can customize blog view a bit by some settings in the <b>Blog</b>
                        section of the edit form:
                    </p>
                    
                    <ul>
                        <li><b>Full view</b> - <i>include body text of listed entries on the blog view</i></li>
                        <li><b>Batch size</b> - <i>select number of entries listed per page</i></li>
                        <li><b>Toolbar enabled</b> - <i>enable / disable the filter toolbar appearance</i></li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <p>
                        After you click on <b>Save</b> button and will be redirected to folder's default view,
                        you can see that whatever view is selected in the <b>Display menu</b> the folder will
                        use our blog view until the folder is activated as blog. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 2.</legend>
                            <img title="Blog created"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/blog_created.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <p><i><b>Note:</b> You can see folder's title and description but only
                        until there are no blog posts as you will see below.</i></p>
                    <p>
                        Now you can start blogging in your new blog folder by adding standard Plone content.
                        Go to blog folder and use default Plone's UI to add new page for example. Again the only
                        trick you need to do is tick the box with label <b>Blog Entry</b> in the <b>Blog</b>
                        section of the content's edit form.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 3.</legend>
                            <img title="Create entry"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/create_entry.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <p><i><b>Note:</b> As with folders you can turn existing content into
                        blog post anytime you want.</i></p>
                    <p>
                        When you save your first blog post and go back to the blog folder, you can see your
                        first entry and new options in the filter toolbar. Also note that blog folder's title
                        and description are hidden by css when at least one entry is available.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 4.</legend>
                            <img title="First entry"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/first_entry.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    
                    <p><i><b>Note:</b> There is additional <b>edit</b> link for quick
                        access to entry edit form just from the blog view if you have permissions
                        to modify an entry.</i></p>
                    
                    <p><i><b>Warning:</b> Blog folder will not list entry which hasn't an effective
                        date which is (by default in Plone) set automatically when content is published. To access
                        not yet published entries (drafts) create a smart folder and link it with
                        <a href="blogging-help#portlet">manage blog portlet</a>.</i></p>
                    
                    <br/>
                    
                    <a name="page-newsitem"></a>
                    <div class="helpTopLink">
                        <a href="blogging-help#top">Go to top</a>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Page and News Item</h3>
                    <p>
                        You can use Plone's <b>Page</b> even <b>News Item</b> content to post an entry in the blog and the only
                        difference is that News Item has a title image with caption which is the same as in Plone
                        itself.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        But it's just about your choice which of these content types you will use since you can put as many
                        as you want images into document's body using <b>WYSIWYG</b> editor.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 5.</legend>
                            <img title="News Item entry"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/news_item_entry.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <br/>

                    <a name="images-files"></a>
                    <div class="helpTopLink">
                        <a href="blogging-help#top">Go to top</a>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Images and Files</h3>
                    <p>
                        Sometimes you want to post into your blog just one image not the whole gallery (which you still
                        can for example using <b>Related Items</b> in combination with any of Plone's content type) so
                        add simple image and mark it as <b>Blog Entry</b> in the same way as in previous cases.<br/>
                        And here we go with a little post containing just an image and description.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 6.</legend>
                            <img title="Image entry"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/image_entry.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <p><i><b>Note:</b> Image of the image entry is not rendered in the right
                        as it is common in the folder summary view because the post is about an image more
                        then a text.</i></p>
                    <p>
                        As simple as with images it is in files case. Just add new file and mark it as <b>Blog Entry</b>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 7.</legend>
                            <img title="File entry"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/file_entry.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <br/>
                    
                    <a name="links-embed-code"></a>
                    <div class="helpTopLink">
                        <a href="blogging-help#top">Go to top</a>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Links and Embed code</h3>
                    <p>
                        If you want to share simple link to some external resources with your comments use Plone's
                        link content type.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 8.</legend>
                            <img title="Link entry"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/link_entry.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <p><i><b>Note:</b> Plone's <b>link auto redirection</b> feature is still
                        working so if user can not modify link based blog post he/she will be redirected
                        to remote url when clicks entry's title in the blog view. So enabling comments
                        on simple link blog entry doesn't make sense.</i></p>
                    <p>
                        Another favorite blogging feature enables you to post any external resource through <b>embed code</b>
                        which is usefull for video posts from <b>YouTube</b>, <b>Google Video</b> or images from <b>Skitch</b>
                        etc. Just add new <b>Link</b> content to the blog and paste an embed code into the textarea labeled
                        as <b>Embed</b> (You can leave default value for remote link field to be ommited from entry's and blog's
                        view).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In case the <b>Embed</b> field is not empty Plone's <b>links auto redirection</b> is disabled.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 9.</legend>
                            <img title="Video entry settings"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/video_entry_settings.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <p><i><b>Note:</b> Embed can be used for other resources or any html code since
                        <b>Embed</b> field contents are just rendered as HTML when rendering whole blog entry.</i></p>
                    <p>
                        After you save new link entry with embed code you get video post with external content.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 10.</legend>
                            <img title="Video entry"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/video_entry.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <br/>
                    
                    <a name="events-maps"></a>
                    <div class="helpTopLink">
                        <a href="blogging-help#top">Go to top</a>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Events and Maps</h3>
                    <p>
                        Sometimes you want to share posts about events whatever it already passed or only will happen.
                        Since Plone provides perfect content type <b>Event</b> for this with a lot of features link
                        ical or vcal support you can create new event and turn it into blog post in the same way
                        as with other content types. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 11.</legend>
                            <img title="Event entry"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/event_entry.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        And becuase events happen in some places it would be nice to show event location on the map.
                        To enable maps feature for blogging events you just need to install additional extra package
                        <b><a href="http://plone.org/products/collective.bloggingmaps">blogging maps</a></b>
                        and you will be available to use Google maps integration to share geo locations.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        There is also additional checkbox to explicitly enable map rendering which is useful only
                        when you want to disable map for the entry since it is not available set <b>no position</b>
                        on the map.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 12.</legend>
                            <img title="Event maps settings"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/event_maps_settings.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        If <b>blogging maps</b> extension is available and you set event's geo location it appeares
                        under event's details. If you want to enable geo location map appearance in the blog view
                        also, go to blog settings and tick the <b>Maps enabled</b> checkbox.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 13.</legend>
                            <img title="Event maps"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/event_maps.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <br />
                    
                    
                    <a name="using-smart-folders"></a>
                    <div class="helpTopLink">
                        <a href="blogging-help#top">Go to top</a>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Using Smart Folders</h3>
                    <p>
                        Basically you will use <b>Folder / Large Folder</b> as container for your blog entries
                        but for personal blog it is common to list posts on site's frontpage which is not so
                        easy in Plone just by selecting folder as default document of the Plone site (add content
                        menu does'nt work as expected at least).<br />
                        So to get your blog appear on the frontpage just create new <b>Smart Folder</b> and enable
                        it as Blog in <b>Blog</b> section of its edit form.<br />
                        Define Smart Folder's criteria usually:
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><b>object_provides</b> &mdash; <i>select <b>collective.bloggin.interfaces.IEntryMarker</b> item from the list</i></li>
                        <li><b>Location</b> &mdash; <i>select your blog's folder (optional)</i></li>
                        <li><b>State</b> &mdash; <i>mostly you will select <b>Published</b></i></li>
                        <li><b>Sort order</b> &mdash; <i>select effective date and tick <b>reverse</b> checkbox</i></li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>
                        <i><b>Note:</b> An <b>object_provides</b> criterium is not available by default.
                            to enable it go to <i><b>Site setup -> Collection</b></i> clik the <b>All fields</b> link. Then find <b>object_provides</b>
                            field and enable it by ticking its checkbox and save changes in the bottom of the page.</i>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        And finally set new smart folder as default document of your site.<br />
                        <b>Warning:</b> Plone's File and Image content has no workflow assigned by default so these types of content
                        are in the same state as parent folder. But common <b>Publish</b> workflow transition also sets
                        object's <b>Effective Date</b> needed for proper blog entries sorting when using SmartFolders.<br />
                        So there are the following options:<br />
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Assign <b>Simple publication workflow</b> to Files and Images in the <b>Types</b> configlet in the
                            <b>Site setup</b> &mdash; <i>recommended</i>
                        </li>
                        <li>Set <b>Effective Date</b> for your File and Image based entries manually.</li>
                    </ul>                    
                    <br />
                    
                    <a name="galleries"></a>
                    <div class="helpTopLink">
                        <a href="blogging-help#top">Go to top</a>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Image Galleries</h3>
                    <p>
                        Sometimes you want to post more then one pictures related to your entry, so you
                        can provide link to external image gallery since there is plenty of foto sharing
                        services.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Those who want to host their pictures locally rather then link to external service,
                        there is simple way how to create your own galleries using <b>Plone Folders</b> with
                        <b>thumbnail view</b> selected in the <b>display</b> menu.<br/>
                        These local galleries can be easily liked to your blog entries using Plone's content
                        field called <b>Related Items</b> which can be found in the <b>Categorization</b>
                        section of each entry's edit form.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <b><i>And as a bonus the blogging package comes with new gallery view which can be
                        selected from the <b>Display</b> menu and you get a simple but fancy picture gallery.
                        </i></b>
                    </p>
                    <br/>
                    
                    <a name="archive-filter"></a>
                    <div class="helpTopLink">
                        <a href="blogging-help#top">Go to top</a>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Archive vs. Filter</h3>
                    <p>
                        Instead of complicated archive views and or auto-moving your posts into
                        generated site structere under the blog folder the <b>Blogging</b> package
                        provides simple entries filtering toolbar which let's you and visitors
                        of your blog to filter older entries.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        You can enable it in the blog settings see <a href="blogging-help#basic-usage">
                            Basic usage</a>
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 14.</legend>
                            <img title="Filter toolbar"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/filter_toolbar.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <i><b>Note:</b> If listed entry is <b>filled under</b> some category and the category
                        link is clicked it filters blog listing by that category.</i>
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        But for those, who likes classic archives listing by years and months, there is also additional
                        archive portlet which will help you with that. Just go to portlets management page and add new
                        <b>Blog archive</b> portlet.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 15.</legend>
                            <img title="Add archive portlet"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/add_archive.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        It requires only to select its blog entries source and optionally option if source blog's
                        title should be included in the portlet's header.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 16.</legend>
                            <img title="Archive portlet settings"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/archive_settings.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        And finally after you save those settings you get simple archvies portlet, but <b>BE AWARE</b> it can be
                        some kind of <b>performance killer</b> when there is a lot of items to count so make sure that it won't
                        slow your blog too much. In all cases its contents are <b>cached for a hour</b>.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 17.</legend>
                            <img title="Archive portlet"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/default_archive.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    
                    <br/>
                    
                    <a name="portlet"></a>
                    <div class="helpTopLink">
                        <a href="blogging-help#top">Go to top</a>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Manage Blog portlet</h3>
                    <p>
                        There is also helper portlet which can help you to quickly post new entries to your
                        blog. To enable it go to Plone's <b>portlets management</b> screen and add new
                        <b>Manage Blog</b> portlet.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 18.</legend>
                            <img title="Add portlet"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/add_portlet.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        You have to select your blog content for which will be the portlet used for. After that you can
                        select which content types should the portlet render creation links for and select your predefined
                        source of drafts (cloven entries) usually represented by some smart folder.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 19.</legend>
                            <img title="Portlet settings"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/portlet_settings.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        After saving the portlet settings you get portlet with direct links for posting new content
                        in your blog. Content creation links are filtered accordingly to allowed content types
                        in referenced blog folder.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 20.</legend>
                            <img title="Default portlet"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/portlet_default.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    
                    <a name="next-prev"></a>
                    <div class="helpTopLink">
                        <a href="blogging-help#top">Go to top</a>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Next / Prev navigation</h3>
                    <p>
                        Plone provides great feature of next / prev navigation for content inside folder but
                        items position in the navigation is calculated by its position in the folder which is not
                        useful for the blog where we list blog entries by its effective date.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        That's why the <b>Blogging</b> package comes with next / prev navigation replacement
                        which do the right navigation items calculation for you. To activate it simple tick
                        the <b>Enable next previous navigation</b> checkbox in your blog folder's edit form.
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        <i><b>Note:</b> Since Plone's Large Folder doesn't support next / prev
                            navigation, there is no next / prev enable checkbox and it is <b>always enabled for Large
                            Folder based blogs.</b></i>
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 21.</legend>
                            <img title="Next / Prev navigation settings"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/next_prev_settings.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Next / Prev navigation replacement will be applied only for folders marked as blog so its
                        default behavior in other cases will not be affected.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 22.</legend>
                            <img title="Next / Prev navigation"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/next_prev_navigation.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <br />
                    
                    <a name="content-rules"></a>
                    <div class="helpTopLink">
                        <a href="blogging-help#top">Go to top</a>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Content rules</h3>
                    <p>
                        It is annoying to tick the <b>Blog entry</b> checkbox every time you
                        create new entry even if all content in the blog folder should be blog entries.
                        That's why the blogging comes with extra <i>content rules action</i> which
                        helps you automate blogging markup.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        There is new action <b>Enable auto-blogging</b> action which is recommended to hang
                        on content creation event and assign to your blog folder. Content creation to automate
                        it at blog posts creation time but give you a change to change it after that.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <fieldset>
                            <legend class="discreet"><tal:block>image</tal:block> 23.</legend>
                            <img title="Content rule action"
                                i18n:attributes="title"
                                src="++resource++collective.blogging.help_images/content_rule.png"/><br/>
                        </fieldset>
                    </p>
                    <br/>
                    
                    <a name="site-view"></a>
                    <div class="helpTopLink">
                        <a href="blogging-help#top">Go to top</a>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Blog as main view for site</h3>
                    <p>

                        You may want the main view of your site being a blog, like it is on <a
                        href="http://lukaszdych.net">lukaszdych.net</a>. Unfortunately it's not possible to
                        <em>blog enable</em> the <em>Plone Site</em>. But you can achieve this with a simple
                        trick:
                    </p>
		    <ul>
		      <li>
			Add a blog as normally: Add folder and check <b>Blog enabled</b> on the <b>Blog</b>-tab
			of the folders properties. For this example we name this Folder <em>Articles</em>.
		      </li>
		      <li>
			Now add a <em>Collection</em>, lets call it <em>MyBlog</em>, to the root folder of your
			Plone Site. Set criterias to select all published content from the <em>Articles</em> folder.
		      </li>
		      <li>
			Add and configure any portlet you may want for this blog.
		      </li>
		      <li>
			Now make <em>MyBlog</em> a blog, too (by checking <b>Blog enabled</b>). This will allow
			all view settings for a blog to be set on the collection. (Note: The collection still
			is no <em>blog</em>, thus you can not use this collection as a target-blog.)
		      </li>
		      <li>
			At last, make <em>MyBlog</em> the default view of your Plone Site.
		      </li>
		    </ul>
                    <br/>

